# Part 2 — Overloading vs Overriding  
### (Same Word Root, Completely Different Beasts)
## 
2️⃣
 Conceptual Distinction
Fill out the table:
| Feature               | Overloading | Overriding |
| --------------------- | ----------- | ---------- |
| Resolved at           | compile time          | runtime      |
| Requires inheritance  | no                    | yes          |
| Same function name    | yes                   | yes          |
| Same parameter list   | no                    | yes          |
| Polymorphism involved | static                | dynamic      |
Then answer:

1. Why is **overloading** a *compile-time convenience*?
Because the compiler selects the correct function based solely on the parameter list at compile time, allowing multiple logically related functions to share the same name without adding new semantics to the type syste
2. Why is **overriding** a *runtime contract*?
Because a derived class promises to provide its own implementation of a base class function, and the function call is resolved at runtime through dynamic dispatch.
3. Why do beginners confuse the two?
because they use the same function name
4. Why is that confusion dangerous?
because Forgetting virtual leads to accidental overloading instead of overriding.
> Hint: The compiler is not your therapist. It will not guess your intent.--
# Part 3 — Constructors & Initialization Lists  
### (Where C++ Stops Holding Your Hand)
## 
3️⃣
 Initialization Lists or Else
Given:
```cpp
class Widget {
private:
const int id;
std::string name;
public:
Widget(int id, std::string name);
};
```
Answer:
1. Why **must** this constructor use an initialization list?
Because id is const, and const data members must be initialized at the moment the object is constructed, not assigned afterward.
2. What happens if you try to assign `id` inside the constructor body?
Because by the time the constructor body executes, id has already been default-initialized, and const objects cannot be reassigned.
